title.narrative: OUTPUT 3.3 HEALTH COMMUNITY ENGAGEMENT

description.narrative: By 2024, families and communities are equipped with knowledge and actively demand quality health services.(UNSDCF Output 1.3), which contributes to Fast-Track The End Of Hiv/Aids, Health And Development In Early Childhood And Adolescence, Immunization Services As Part Of Primary Health Care, Mental Health And Psychosocial Well-Being, Nutrition Of Adolescents And Women, Strengthening Primary Health Care And High-Impact Health Interventions, Strengthening Primary Health Care And High-Impact Health Interventions (Covid). UNICEF aims to achieve this through Community Engagement, Social And Behaviour Change, Developing And Leveraging Resources And Partnerships, Harnessing Power Of Business And Markets, Systems Strengthening And Institution Building, Systems Strengthening To Leave No One Behind. This contributes to the following Country Programme result: By 2024: Significantly more girls, boys, adolescents and women, especially those who are marginalized and/or living in humanitarian conditions, have access to and utilize evidence-based, high-impact quality maternal, neonatal, child, adolescent health, and HIV interventions.

description.narrative: UNICEF mobilized local communities by engaging them through social behaviour change communication initiatives to increase access to and use of health services. During the campaigns conducted – COVID-19, typhoid and nOPV – culturally sensitive and appropriate information was provided to enable individuals to demand and receive the vaccines. The campaigns also battled misinformation, rumours and vaccine hesitancy, resulting in a decrease in the proportion of missed children from 8.4% to 4.4%. The percentage of people who believed rumours decreased from 0.7% to 0.2% in the two rounds conducted, with ‘rumours about COVID-19’ being the main reason for refusals | Status:On-track | As-of Date:25/01/2022
